Anonymous Sat 29 Jun 2024 20:34:36 No.67002277 Report
Quoted By: >>67002520 >>67002541 >>67002583 >>67002585 >>67002618
People were talking about Pinwheel a couple of threads back and I didn't get a chance to reply before it 404'd.

>no drones
Autonomous weapons are banned by the UN due to grisly African bush wars that involved loitering munitions and drones playing recordings of people screaming for help to lure enemy soldiers. Snek has said that his narrative reasoning for this is mostly because drones lower the stakes and remove humans from a lot of battlefield roles.
Can't have stories about tankers or pilots if everything is autonomous.
>no supersoldiers
Genetic engineering and cybernetic augmentation are banned by the Yellow Sea Treaty, which was penned after a war between the US and China where disposable supersoldiers were fielded that later melted due to shoddy CRISPR tech.
The thing is, the UNN only kind of follows those rules. There are in fact cybernetic supersoldiers called SWAR who run black ops and are fielded by corrupt admirals. They get around the treaty by claiming their amputations are due to battlefield injury (they're not). These guys show up as villains in a couple of stories.
>other species don't follow these rules
These treaties exist inside the UN and other races aren't signatories. The UN doesn't rule the Coalition, they're just members.

I think it's weird when people get up in arms about the UN being the good guys, because the whole premise of the setting is that it's a positive future where humanity has improved. Snek has said that he wants humanity to be a force for good and to always leave things better than they found them.
So many people want it to be 40k where it's just a parade of misery all the time and I don't get that. The UNN isn't going to glass civilian population centers or use germ weapons, even if they have the capability to do so. They're also not all good, and it's honestly kind of predictable how many of the admirals are secret bad guys at this point.
